My partner had found this gem on a previous trip to NYC and has not stopped talking about how amazing the dumplings are for the last year. Now I understand why. The restaurant is very clean and the staff is friendly while remaining extremely efficient. Food is served promptly and it is very fresh. Fortunately we were splitting everything we ordered or it might have been awkward when the entrees arrived separately, especially since the appetizer had yet to arrive. Despite that, this place remains 5 stars in my book. Best of all, the lunch prices are cheaper than back home in the Midwest. The food was so flavorful that I will probably be dreaming of it for years. We had the twice cooked pork and curry chicken lunch entrees that came with rice and a delightful soup. I have to start by saying that I usually dislike Chinese curries, but this one came recommended by our server and it was AMAZING. The twice cooked pork was even better though. There was no description on the menu, but it is basically pork, bok choy, tofu and carrots in a bright red chili sauce that was not hot at all with robust flavors that blended so well, I could not easily identify them. We also had the duck and crab dumplings. These were filled with meat that was finely ground and formed into perfect balls of pure delight. Along with the meat was a broth that was perfectly clear and had rich meaty flavors that perfectly complemented the dumpling dough. As great as the rest of the meal was, I would have been completely content to eat nothing but these dumpling for the entire meal. Finally we finished the meal with a red bean pancake. This fried delicacy is mildly sweet with the big flavors you get from deep frying dough.

Can we all just take a moment of silence for the soup dumplings? They are incredible. We have been here multiple times and always leave more than satisfied. (tea charge was already more than 30% of my food though) I might misunderstanding them but they started complaining in both Eng and Chinese that I should give them extra tips too! A bit off the beaten path but serves one of the best soup dumplings in Manhattan. Almost never more than a 10-25 minutes wait. Do yourself s favor and avoid Joe's Shanghai and check this place out if you're in the mood for some soup dumplings.
